% Automatisch generiert — Thema: Marijuana Legalization
% arg/1 Fakten
arg(pro82).  % [pro] But with legalization, proper means to settle disputes would be created.
arg(pro15).  % [pro] 27% of supporters say legalization would lead to improved regulation of marijuana.
arg(pro15b).  % [pro] 27% of supporters say legalization would lead to increased tax revenues.
arg(pro4).  % [pro] The paper of record argues that cannabis prohibition creates social costs, supporting legalization.
arg(pro4b).  % [pro] The paper of record argues that cannabis prohibition has a racist history, supporting legalization.
arg(pro4c).  % [pro] The paper of record argues that cannabis prohibition wastes resources, supporting legalization.
arg(pro95).  % [pro] Marijuana also helps medical conditions as a more natural substitute to pharmaceuticals.
arg(pro36).  % [pro] Teen marijuana use has fallen slightly over the past five years.
arg(pro36b).  % [pro] Four states and the District of Columbia have legalized marijuana, and 23 other states allow medical use.
arg(pro32).  % [pro] Though more adults are smoking pot, the MTF data suggests that teens aren't following suit.
arg(pro29).  % [pro] People believe that legalizing recreational weed will cut off a revenue stream for illegal drug traders.
arg(con18).  % [con] There is a good reason why most habitual marijuana users come off as stupid.
arg(con95).  % [con] The study found that even those who quit in adulthood were not able to recover the IQ points.
arg(con14).  % [con] Any time marijuana use is made legal, drug accessibility to children will increase.
arg(con87).  % [con] Marijuana tends to be a starter drug for people who move on to heavier duty drugs, whether those drugs are legal or illegal.
arg(con87b).  % [con] I do not think that having marijuana as a starter drug is something we want for our society.
arg(con87c).  % [con] Society is changing rapidly to a different type of society, and nobody is getting a chance to discuss marijuana legalization.
arg(con115).  % [con] According to social worker Shannon McPherson, marijuana legalization has been bad for the whole Pueblo community.
arg(con70).  % [con] Marijuana is even more toxic than cigarette smoke.
arg(con12).  % [con] Marijuana is terrible for your physical health.

% att/2 Fakten  (Dung 1995 — binär; Typ/conf aus LLM-Kandidaten als Kommentar)
att(pro15, con14).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — Pro15 claims legalization improves regulation, while con14 asserts it increases child accessibility, a logically incompatible outcome.
att(con95, pro82).  % [undermining] conf=70 — con95 cites irreversible IQ loss, questioning the ability of users to engage in proper dispute settlement envisioned by pro82.
att(con18, pro4).  % [undercutting] conf=70 — The claim that habitual users appear "stupid" challenges the conclusion that legalization is beneficial by suggesting harmful effects of use.
att(con95, pro4).  % [undercutting] conf=75 — Evidence of irreversible IQ loss undermines the pro‑legalization conclusion by showing a serious negative consequence of marijuana use.
att(con14, pro4).  % [rebuttal] conf=80 — con14 claims legalization harms children, directly contradicting pro4’s claim that legalization is justified
att(con87, pro4).  % [rebuttal] conf=75 — con87 asserts marijuana is a gateway to harder drugs, opposing pro4’s endorsement of legalization
att(con87b, pro4).  % [rebuttal] conf=70 — con87b states society should not accept marijuana as a starter drug, conflicting with pro4’s pro‑legalization stance
att(con115, pro4).  % [rebuttal] conf=80 — con115 reports that legalization has been harmful, directly opposing pro4’s claim that legalization is beneficial
att(con115, pro4b).  % [rebuttal] conf=85 — Con115 concludes legalization is harmful, directly contradicting pro4b’s conclusion that legalization is justified.
att(con12, pro4b).  % [undercutting] conf=70 — con12 argues health harms, showing that a racist history alone may not justify legalization
att(con18, pro4c).  % [undercutting] conf=65 — con18 highlights negative user outcomes, questioning whether resource waste justifies legalization
att(con95, pro4c).  % [undercutting] conf=70 — con95 shows lasting cognitive damage, undermining the claim that waste alone warrants legalization
att(con14, pro4c).  % [rebuttal] conf=80 — con14 claims legalization increases child access, directly opposing pro4c’s pro‑legalization stance
att(con87, pro4c).  % [rebuttal] conf=75 — con87 argues legalization creates a gateway to harder drugs, contradicting pro4c’s justification for legalization
att(pro4c, con87b).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — Pro argues legalization while con opposes marijuana as a starter drug, directly contradicting the policy conclusion
att(pro4c, con115).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — Pro supports legalization whereas con claims legalization has harmed a community, making the conclusions mutually exclusive
